<div class="grid-container grid-x body-content">
	<div class="cell large-12 small-12 main-content-well">
		<div class="story-content">
							<div class="story-info">
			<div class="featured-img-container">
			<img class="story-img" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/lhfavestories2025-copy.jpg" title="Our Favorite Lit Hub Stories From 2025">
								</div>
		<div class="story-heads">
		<h1>Our Favorite Lit Hub Stories From 2025</h1>
		<h2>The Editors Pick the Best Writing at the Site This Year</h2>	</div>
	</div>
										<div class="byline-date">
					<span class="byline"><a href="https://lithub.com/author/literary-hub/"  title="Literary Hub">Literary Hub</a></span>
					<span class="hr"></span>
					<span class="date">December 25, 2025</span>
				</div>
						<div class="story-body">
								<p>From essays to interviews, excerpts to blog posts, reading lists to poems, we publish a lot of good stuff at Lit Hub, if we do say so ourselves. And while we are proud of all of the pieces weâ€™ve shared in 2025, we all have our personal favorites. Below are a few of the Lit Hub features the staff loved best from this past year.</p>
<p><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="262405" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/maybe-dont-talk-to-the-new-york-times-about-zohran-mamdani/zohran-mamdani/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/zohran-mamdani.jpg" data-orig-size="2450,1225" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="zohran mamdani" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/zohran-mamdani-300x150.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/zohran-mamdani-1240x620.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-262405" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/zohran-mamdani.jpg" alt="" width="2450" height="1225" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/zohran-mamdani.jpg 2450w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/zohran-mamdani-300x150.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/zohran-mamdani-1240x620.jpg 1240w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/zohran-mamdani-768x384.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/zohran-mamdani-60x30.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/zohran-mamdani-1536x768.jpg 1536w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/zohran-mamdani-2048x1024.jpg 2048w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/zohran-mamdani-50x25.jpg 50w" sizes="(max-width: 2450px) 100vw, 2450px" /></p>
<h3 style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://lithub.com/maybe-dont-talk-to-the-new-york-times-about-zohran-mamdani/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Maybe Donâ€™t Talk to the <em>New York Times</em> About Zohran Mamdani</a><br />
</strong>Peter Coviello</h3>
<p>Sometimes, you read one of those essays that makes you sit up and go ðŸ‘€. So it was with this piece from Peter Coviello, a passionate and inspired analysis of the obsessive both-sides-ism of legacy media outlets like <em>The New York Times</em> and how that kind of flawed reporting has ruined this countryâ€™s collective brains. Coviello gets in some good licks at the likes of David Brooks (always welcome, in my household) but more than that, he reminds us that weâ€”the readers, the peopleâ€”are the ones who endow an outlet like the <em>NYT</em> with power, not the other way around. Perhaps we should stop talking to the <em>Times</em>, or stop reading it. Maybe we can insist on reportage that actually reflects the world we live in, not the world of the elites that they are so desperate to hang onto. Or, if not, at least we can keep reading essays like this one. <em>â€“Drew Broussard, Podcasts Editor</em></p>
