<h3 style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://lithub.com/gaza-through-yeatss-gyre/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The View From Gazaâ€”As Seen Through WB Yeatsâ€™s Widening Gyre</a></strong><br />
Alaa Alqaisi</h3>
<p>â€œSomeone, somewhere, must remember that we were human here. Even in the hour of ash. Even as the gyre devours the sun.â€</p>
<p>Writing from inside the besieged strip, Alaa Alqaisiâ€™s haunting, lyrical essay considers the annihilation of Gazaâ€”which she sees as â€œthe trembling fulcrum upon which the gyre of moral collapse turnsâ€â€”through the lens of Yeatsâ€™ apocalyptic 1919 poem, â€œThe Second Coming.â€ Itâ€™s a hypnotic, terrifying piece of writing; a reckoning with the breakdown of language itself in the face of this â€œsustained dismantling of the soul.â€ To conjure something like this, with terror and starvation plaguing you at every waking moment, is nothing short of astonishing. <em>â€“Dan Sheehan, Book Marks Editor-in-Chief</em></p>
