<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="257879" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/why-thomas-pynchons-vineland-a-disappointment-when-it-was-published-is-the-novel-we-need-right-now/pynchon-5/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/pynchon.jpg" data-orig-size="1650,674" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="pynchon" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/pynchon-300x123.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/pynchon-1240x507.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-257879" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/pynchon.jpg" alt="" width="1650" height="674" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/pynchon.jpg 1650w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/pynchon-300x123.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/pynchon-1240x507.jpg 1240w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/pynchon-768x314.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/pynchon-60x25.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/pynchon-1536x627.jpg 1536w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/pynchon-50x20.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1650px) 100vw, 1650px" /></p>
<h3 style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/why-thomas-pynchons-vineland-a-disappointment-when-it-was-published-is-the-novel-we-need-right-now/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Why Thomas Pynchonâ€™s <em>Vineland</em>â€”a Disappointment When It Was Publishedâ€”is the Novel We Need Right Now</strong></a><br />
Devin Thomas Oâ€™Shea</h3>
<p>Out of all the big contemporary films taking on political violence, <em>One Battle After Another</em> was the most successful and interesting to me, better than the snotty <em>Eddington</em> and the loopy <em>Bugonia</em>. The movie sent a lot of us hunting for PTAâ€™s source material, Pynchonâ€™s <em>Vineland</em>, which seems to have kicked off a wild supply and demand cycleâ€”the markup on the secondary market has been pretty wild. Anecdotally, I could only find way-too-expensive copies in NYC bookstores, and I tried to order a used copy online twice, only to have both orders canceled because the book in question had already been sold. I finally got my hands on a reasonably priced <em>Vineland</em> at a used bookstore in upstate NY, but safe to say people are <em>Vine</em>&#8216; crazy.</p>
<p>Oâ€™Sheaâ€™s essay is less a close reading of <em>Vineland</em> as it is about Pynchonâ€™s work more broadly, and how the 1990 novel fits into the author&#8217;s understanding of American politics, military-industrialism, and the particularly American ritualized, sexualized violence: â€œIf you had to point to one continuous theme in all of Pynchonâ€™s work, it is a silver Christian fish bumper sticker turned right-side up to look like a rocket,â€ Oâ€™Shea writes.</p>
<p>Pynchon has clear interests and Oâ€™Shea charts the reclusive authorâ€™s obsessions across his books and the fragments of his biography that are available. It makes for a great starting place to understand the themes that went into PTAâ€™s film, especially if youâ€™re still searching for your own <em>Vineland</em> out there. <em>â€“JF</em></p>
