<h3 style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/anna-north-thinks-about-the-roman-empire-all-the-time/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Anna North Thinks About the Roman Empire All the Time</strong></a><br />
Anna North</h3>
<p>I loved this short personal account of the Latin nerdâ€™s dilemma of getting hooked on a dead language. I too studied Latin for probably too long, and was also given the advice to not waste my time. But as North explains: Latin rocks.</p>
<p>Sure, you have the best answers to the â€œhow often do you think about the Roman Empireâ€ meme, and you have a better grasp of grammar than most. But whatâ€™s wonderful about a foundation in Latin is how it vividly reveals the consistency of the human experience. The concerns of the past are, of course, the concerns of the present. Reading Latin is a kind of time travelâ€”â€œI find it moving that the beauty and humor of Latin literature endures,â€ North writes, â€œthousands of years after its writing.â€ <em>â€“JF</em></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
