<h3 style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/actually-master-and-commander-is-a-domestic-fantasy-about-a-codependent-life-partnership/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Actually, <em>Master and Commander</em> is a Domestic Fantasy About a Codependent Life Partnership!</strong></a><br />
Olivia Wolfgang-Smith</h3>
<p>I canâ€™t stop referencing this essay, which is maybe a bit too revealing about how often the Aubreyâ€“Maturin books come up in my life. The title makes for a great conversation starter, and is one of those statements that becomes more obvious the more you think about it.</p>
<p>Wolfgang-Smithâ€™s argument that Patrick Oâ€™Brianâ€™s epic book cycle is â€œa work of domestic fantasyâ€ is not just convincing, but enriching. The books are (not incorrectly) slotted as â€œclassic Fatherâ€™s Day gift material,â€ but her closer reading does justice to the depth and development of character in Oâ€™Brianâ€™s work. If you come to these books looking just for swashbuckling, you might be surprised by the long sections that take place in the quiet of a shipâ€™s cabin over music and wine, or on land, with the grounded chores of bills, property, and attending to failing mining investments.</p>
<p>What Wolfgang-Smith articulates is how the experience of reading Oâ€™Brianâ€™s twenty books starts to blur into patterns that are instantly recognizable to anyone in a long term relationship. â€œOâ€™Brian has the two men fit themselves to one otherâ€™s blind spots,â€ she writes, and he uses repeated settings, phrases, and even the same year to build the comfortable feeling that comes with commitment and intimacy.</p>
<p>â€œWhat is life, after all,â€ Wolfgang-Smith writes, â€œbut a serialized adventure?â€ <em>â€“JF</em></p>
